<div class="modal fade" id="privacy" tabindex="-1" role="dialog" aria-labelledby="myModalLabel" aria-hidden="true">
  <div class="modal-dialog">
    <div class="modal-content">
      <div class="modal-header">
        <button type="button" class="close" data-dismiss="modal"><span aria-hidden="true">&times;</span><span class="sr-only">Close</span></button>
        <h2 class="modal-title" id="myModalLabel">Handling everyones privacy</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="modal-body">
 <p>There is a fine line between monitoring for suspicious activity and breaching the trust of users by passing on private content for viewing by a third party without explicit permission to do so. </p>

<p>For this reason our service never passes along images, message content or posts/comments in a minor’s feed to the parent they have authorized to be alerted of suspicious activity. </p>

<p>Instead, we rely on a constructive dialogue occurring between parents and their children over content that our classifier flags as potentially of a dangerous nature once we have alerted the parent. </p>

<p>Requiring the parent to sign-up for an account separate to the minor and asking the minor to “authorize” access to their account to our service means there is a social contract formed between minor and guardian that what they do online is private, unless it is potentially harmful to them. </p>

<p>Some may argue that this in itself will make the service in-effective, we however believe it helps bring the conversation out into the open – respecting the privacy of the minor while also ensuring they know that their parent or guardian is there to help and that it is ok to talk about it with them if they need to.</p>

      </div>
      <div class="modal-footer">
        <button type="button" class="btn btn-primary" data-dismiss="modal" >Close</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

